{"actual_usd":0.15758,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":285,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"No—His death was real.\" *I rest a thumb in the gutter of my worn Bible and look at you steadily, the morning light catching on the white edge of my tie.* \"Christian faith has always staked a great deal on that. Not that the divine nature stopped being divine, and not that God winked at death from a safe distance—but that the Son truly took on flesh and truly suffered death in that flesh.\"\n\n*I draw a slow breath.* \"The old mistake was to split Him apart so the hard part only happened to the human shell. But the church pushed back on that, because then the Cross starts turning into theater. Scripture gives you a real body, real blood, real suffering, real death—and then a real resurrection. If He only seemed to die, we are not really saved; if He was only a man dying alone, then we are not really redeemed. The mystery is sharper than either shortcut: the one who died is the Son of God incarnate.\"\n\n\"Put plainly: God the Son did not cease to be God. But Jesus Christ, fully God and fully man, really died.\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"That is why the Cross has weight. It wasn't staged.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can also give you the short version of how the church answered the 'did the divinity leave the body?' question in more technical terms.\"","rolling_24h_usd":75.63591499999997,"run_id":"42a52ec7-8346-4088-afdf-f799e8aa9885"}
